2026-03-15 | Fancy Sequence API

•	Operations:
	1. append(val)
		Add a new value to the sequence.

	2. addAll(inc)
		Add inc to every existing value.

	3. multAll(m)
		Multiply every existing value by m.

	4. getIndex(idx)
		Return the value at index idx.

•	Constraints are large, so updating the entire array each time would be too slow.

	Key Idea
Use **lazy linear transformation**.

Every element undergoes operations of the form:

		value = value * mul + add

We keep two global variables:
		globalMul
		globalAdd

Instead of updating every element, we adjust these variables.

When appending a value:
We store its normalized form by reversing the current transformation.

	Time Complexity
		append → O(1)  
		addAll → O(1)  
		multAll → O(1)  
		getIndex → O(1)

	Space Complexity
		O(n)

	Solution

class Fancy {
public:
    const long long MOD = 1e9 + 7;

    vector<long long> arr;
    long long mul = 1;
    long long add = 0;

    long long modInverse(long long x){
        long long res = 1, p = MOD-2;

        while(p){
            if(p&1) res = (res*x)%MOD;
            x = (x*x)%MOD;
            p >>= 1;
        }

        return res;
    }

    Fancy() {}

    void append(int val) {
        long long inv = modInverse(mul);
        long long v = ((val - add + MOD) % MOD * inv) % MOD;
        arr.push_back(v);
    }

    void addAll(int inc) {
        add = (add + inc) % MOD;
    }

    void multAll(int m) {
        mul = (mul * m) % MOD;
        add = (add * m) % MOD;
    }

    int getIndex(int idx) {
        if(idx >= arr.size()) return -1;

        long long val = arr[idx];
        return (val * mul % MOD + add) % MOD;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Instead of updating every element on each operation, we maintain a **global affine transformation**:

		value → value × mul + add

New elements are inserted in normalized form so that when the transformation is applied later, the correct value is obtained.
